'''Yéremy Jesús Pino Santos''' (born 20 October 2002) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] or [[Winger (association football)|winger]] for {{English football updater|CrystalP}} club [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] and the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]].

An [[Villarreal CF (youth)|academy graduate]] of [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]], Pino made his first-team debut in 2020, and started as Villarreal won the [[2021 UEFA Europa League final]] in his first season, becoming the youngest player to win the competition. He later left Villarreal and signed with English club Crystal Palace in August 2025, winning the [[2026 UEFA Conference League final|UEFA Conference League]] in his first season.

Pino represented Spain at various [[Spain national youth football team|youth levels]] before making his senior international debut in 2021 and being included in the squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]. He was part of the squad that won the [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League]], starting in [[2023 UEFA Nations League final|the final]].

==Club career==
===Villareal===
====Early career====
Pino was born in [[Las Palmas]], [[Canary Islands]], and joined [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]]' youth setup in 2014, after representing [[AD Huracán|Huracán]] and Barrio Atlántico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rodagonsport.com/index.php/noticias/311-yeremi-la-copa-rodagon-es-un-torneo-muy-especial-para-mi|title=Yéremi: "La Copa Rodagon es un torneo muy especial para mí"|trans-title=Yéremi: "The Rodagon Cup is a very special tournament for me"|website=Rodagon Sport|language=es|date=20 February 2019|access-date=22 November 2020|archive-date=6 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211006223805/http://www.rodagonsport.com/index.php/noticias/311-yeremi-la-copa-rodagon-es-un-torneo-muy-especial-para-mi|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 22 June 2017, after turning down an offer from [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], he signed for [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laprovincia.es/ud-las-palmas/2017/06/22/yeremi-rechaza-oferta-barca-ficha-9683606.html|title=Yéremi rechaza la oferta del Barça y ficha en el Villarreal|trans-title=Yéremi refuses the offer of ''Barça'' and signs for Villarreal|first=Mario|last=García de laSanta|publisher=La Provincia|language=es|date=22 June 2017}}</ref>

Pino made his senior debut with [[Villarreal CF C|the C-team]] on 24 August 2019, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Fernando Niño (footballer, born 2000)|Fer Niño]] and scoring the third of a 3–0 [[Tercera División]] away win against [[CF Recambios Colón|Recambios Colón]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://golsmedia.com/comunidad-valenciana/futbol/recambios-colon-cd/2019/08/24/villarreal-c-demostro-sus-hechuras-perdiguer/|title=El Villarreal CF C demostró sus hechuras y ganó bien en El Perdiguer|trans-title=Villarreal C show their size and win comfortably at the El Perdiguer|publisher=Golsmedia|language=es|date=24 August 2019|access-date=22 November 2020}}</ref> After finishing [[2019–20 Tercera División|his first senior season]] with three goals in 20 appearances, he was promoted to [[Villarreal CF B|the reserves]] in [[Segunda División B]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2025}}

====2020–21 season====
After spending the pre-season with the first team under [[Unai Emery]], Pino made his professional debut on 22 October 2020, replacing [[Francis Coquelin]] in a 5–3 [[2020–21 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] victory against [[Sivasspor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2029721/|title=Villarreal 5–3 Sivasspor|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=22 October 2020|access-date=22 November 2020}}</ref> He made his [[La Liga]] debut three days later, again from the bench in a 0–0 draw at [[Cádiz CF|Cádiz]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/primera-division/cadiz-vs-villarreal/cronica/2020/10/25/5f957ecae2704e56748b457f.html|title=La única que gana es la lógica|trans-title=The only one who wins is logic|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|publisher=Unidad Editorial|language=es|date=25 October 2020|access-date=22 November 2020}}</ref>

Pino scored his first professional goal on 29 October 2020, netting the equalizer in a 3–1 away success over [[Qarabağ FK|Qarabağ]] also in the European competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2029733--qarabag-vs-villarreal/|title=Qarabağ 1–3 Villarreal|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=29 October 2020|access-date=22 November 2020}}</ref> On 12 November, he renewed his contract with the club until 2024.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/villarreal/villarreal-renueva-blinda-baena-yeremi-pino-jorgensen-fer-nino-8201227|title=El Villarreal renueva y blinda a Baena, Yeremi Pino, Jorgensen y Fer Niño|trans-title=Villarreal renew and shield Baena, Yeremi Pino, Jorgensen and Fer Niño|newspaper=[[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]]|language=es|date=12 November 2020|access-date=22 November 2020}}</ref> On 26 May 2021, Pino played in the [[2021 UEFA Europa League Final]] – becoming the youngest Spanish player to start a major European final, aged 18 years and 218 days – breaking the previous record of [[Iker Casillas]] in the [[2000 UEFA Champions League Final]], aged 19 years and 4 days.<ref name="auto1">{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0269-125f1aaaeb0d-c59e8a06ac14-1000--villarreal-1-1-manchester-united-aet-11-10-pens-spanish-side/ |title=Villarreal 1–1 Manchester United (aet, 11–10 pens): Spanish side win Europa League in marathon shoot-out |website=UEFA |date=26 May 2021 }}</ref> He also became the youngest player to win the competition, eclipsing the record set by [[Robin van Persie]] in the [[2002 UEFA Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-my/news/yeremy-pino-villarreal-wonderkid-rejected-barcelona/d5ry69ihu4rb155hxj2p0ne1c |title=Yeremy Pino: Villarreal wonderkid who rejected Barcelona |website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=26 May 2021 }}</ref>

====2021–22 season and beyond====
Pino scored four times on 27 February 2022 as Villarreal won 5–1 at home to [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]], having only two goals for the season to his name before the game. He also became the youngest player to score a hat-trick in the first half of a La Liga match.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Martin |first=Richard |title=Ronaldo, Messi, Suarez, Griezmann and... Yeremy Pino |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/us/news/ronaldo-messi-suarez-griezmann-and-yeremy-pino |access-date=6 June 2025|magazine=[[FourFourTwo]] |date=27 February 2022}}</ref> In November 2023, he tore the anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) in his left knee, and was ruled out for the rest of the [[2023–24 Villarreal CF season|2023–24 season]], making his return the following summer.<ref name=injury>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6581143/2025/08/29/yeremy-pino-crystal-palace-transfer/|title=Yeremy Pino to Crystal Palace: Everything you need to know|last=Weatherspoon|first=Chris|website=The Athletic|date=29 August 2025}}</ref>

===Crystal Palace===
On 29 August 2025, Pino signed for [[Premier League]] club [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in a deal worth £26 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/announcement/crystal-palace-sign-yeremy-pino-villarreal/|title=Palace sign Yeremy Pino from Villarreal|publisher=Crystal Palace F.C.|date=29 August 2025|accessdate=29 August 2025}}</ref> He was assigned the number 10 shirt, replacing the departing [[Eberechi Eze]], who moved to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/clyd0n3411eo|title=Palace sign Spain winger Pino from Villarreal
|website=BBC Sport|date=29 August 2025}}</ref>

On 2 October 2025, Pino registered his first two goal contributions for Palace, assisting both [[Daniel Muñoz (footballer)|Daniel Muñoz]] and [[Eddie Nketiah]] in a 2–0 away win over [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]] in the [[2025–26 UEFA Conference League|UEFA Conference League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cewnzyx1yvyt|title=Dynamo Kyiv 0–2 Crystal Palace|website=BBC Sport|date=2 October 2025}}</ref> Pino scored his first goal for Crystal Palace in their 3–0 win over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the fourth round of the [[2025–26 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] on 29 October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cvgdvrn1wg8t|title=Liverpool 0–3 Crystal Palace: Arne Slot's selection backfires as Eagles win in EFL Cup last 16|website=BBC|date=29 October 2025|access-date=30 October 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
Pino represented Spain at [[Spain national under-17 football team|under-17]] and [[Spain national under-18 football team|under-18]] levels, also acting as [[Captain (association football)|team captain]] for the latter side.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://villarrealcf.es/en/news/item/26424-yeremi-pino-shines-with-spain-u18s|title=Yeremi Pino shines with Spain U18s|first=Fran|last=Segovia|website=Villarreal CF|date=12 December 2019}}</ref> Due to the isolation of some national team players following the positive [[COVID-19]] test of [[Sergio Busquets]], Spain's under-21 squad were called up for the international friendly against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] on 8 June 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sefutbol.com/oficial-lista-convocados-encuentro-lituania |title=Oficial {{!}} Lista de convocados para el encuentro ante Lituania |trans-title=Official {{!}} Squad list for the match against Lithuania |publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] |date=6 June 2021 |access-date=7 June 2021 |language=es |archive-date=8 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211008070336/https://sefutbol.com/oficial-lista-convocados-encuentro-lituania |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Pino made his debut for the [[Spain national football team|senior squad]] on 6 October 2021 in the [[2021 UEFA Nations League Finals|2021 UEFA Nations League]] semi-final against [[Italy national football team|Italy]], replacing the injured [[Ferran Torres]] after 49 minutes in a 2–1 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Debuta el grancanario Yéremi [''sic''] Pino con la selección frente a Italia|trans-title=Gran Canaria native Yeremi Pino debuts with the national team against Italy |url=https://www.canarias7.es/deportes/futbol/debuta-grancanario-yeremi-20211006222021-nt.html |access-date=5 April 2022 |publisher=Canarias7 |date=6 October 2021 |language=es}}</ref> Four days later, he came off the bench for [[Pablo Sarabia]] in a defeat by the same score in the [[2021 UEFA Nations League final|final]] against [[France national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite news |title=España juega pero Francia impone sus golpes y se lleva la Liga de Naciones|trans-title=Spain play but France dish out their blows and lift the Nations League |url=https://www.france24.com/es/minuto-a-minuto/20211010-espa%C3%B1a-juega-pero-francia-impone-sus-golpes-y-se-lleva-la-liga-de-naciones |access-date=5 April 2022 |publisher=[[France 24]] |date=10 October 2021 |language=es}}</ref>

Pino's first start for Spain came on 29 March 2022 in a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]] against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] in [[A Coruña]], scoring his first goal in a 5–0 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain 5–0 Iceland |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60921671 |access-date=5 April 2022 |website=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=29 March 2022}}</ref> He was later included in Spain's squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], though he was an unused subtitute throughout the tournament.

On 15 June 2023, Pino scored the opener in a 2–1 victory over Italy in the [[2023 UEFA Nations League Finals|2023 UEFA Nations League]] semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65922637|title=Spain 2–1 Italy: Joselu winner sends La Roja to Nations League final|date=15 June 2023|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He started in the final three days later against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], winning his first international trophy as Spain triumphed on penalties following a 0–0 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65944659|title=Croatia 0–0 Spain (Pens: 4–5): Spaniards win Nations League for first title in 11 years|website=BBC Sport|date=18 June 2023}}</ref>

Due to his anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) tear in November 2023, Pino was unable to take part in [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref name=injury/> He made his return to the national team against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] on 8 September 2024, and later came off the bench for [[Lamine Yamal]] in the [[2025 UEFA Nations League final]] on 8 June 2025 as Spain lost on penalties to [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cvgqzyl24j4t#Line-ups|title=Portugal 2–2 Spain (5–3 after pens)|date=8 June 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

